"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522193","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>Guidelines on overseas police deployments include detail on when approval from the Home Office is required under section 26 of the Police Act 1996.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-06-06T12:30:21.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522193/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522193/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Police: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answers of 23 May 2016 to Questions 37209 and 37235, whether official guidelines on the policing of football matches abroad state that authority must be granted by her Department under section 26 of the Police Act 1996 to permit UK police officers to perform operational police duties abroad.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","38859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522194","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Home Office does not hold information on curfew orders issued for anti-social behaviour.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-06-06T13:00:17.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522194/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522194/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Curfews: Stafford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many curfew orders have been issued for anti-social behaviour in Stafford constituency since the introduction of such orders.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","38843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522195","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Crime Survey statistics published by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) show that crime in England and Wales fell by 7% in the year to the end of December 2015 (the latest period for which data is available), and has fallen by well over a quarter since 2010.</p><p>Over the same period, crimes recorded by the police have risen. The independent ONS has been clear that rises in police recorded crime are largely the result of more victims coming forward to report certain offences and improvements in police crime recording practices. Police recorded crime for the Stafford constituency for the last three years is shown in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-06-06T16:15:43.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522195/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522195/answer","Table 38844.xlsx","Table 38844.xlsx","Recorded crime figures","Recorded crime figures","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522195/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Crime: Stafford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the trends in the level of crime in Stafford constituency in each of the last three years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","38844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522196","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Home Office do not hold the information requested. The responsibility for recording fraud offences transferred to Action Fraud from individual police forces between April 2011 and March 2013. Therefore, no fraud offences should have been recorded by Staffordshire police since then.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice do not hold the information requested on prosecutions and convictions.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-06-06T12:57:12.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522196/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522196/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many offences involving the fraudulent use of personal information have been reported to Staffordshire Police in each year since 2006; and how many such reports led to a (a) prosecution and (b) conviction.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","38840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522197","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>The UK Government has invested tens of millions of pounds to reinforce border security through infrastructure improvements at the Juxtaposed ports, and continues to work closely with the French authorities at both political and operational levels. The vast majority of the security work identified in the Joint Declaration has been completed including the installation of 52 miles worth of critical security fencing, advanced anti-intrusion measures such as infra-red cameras, thermal detection cameras and floodlighting in key areas.</p><p>In addition to this the UK has funded security guards and since June 2015 doubled Border Force contractor freight searching and dog detection capability at the juxtaposed controls. To help coordinate the law enforcement response from the UK and France a joint command and control centre has been established. The investment in security by the UK, the closer coordination of our law enforcement response and the significant investment in police resources by the French Government, has significantly improved the security situation in Northern France.</p><p>The UK and France regularly review security at the ports to ensure the new measures are maintained and remain effective. Furthermore, at the UK-France summit in Amiens on 3 March, the Home Secretary announced that the UK will contribute £17 million over the next financial year to joint work with France to ease migrant pressures in the Calais region and further strengthen the UK border.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-09T16:56:38.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522197/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522197/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Borders: France","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Managing migratory flows in Calais: joint ministerial declaration on UK/French co-operation, published on 20 August 2015, what progress has been made on implementing the measures in that declaration to reinforce border security in northern France where the UK operates a juxtaposed border control.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","38888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522198","Home Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We continue to work closely with a wide range of local authorities across the UK to increase the number of areas that accommodate and support people seeking asylum and protection.</p><p>I am reassured that the number of local authorities participating in the dispersal scheme continues to increase. I intend therefore only to write to specific local authority leaders if progress is unsatisfactory.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-27T09:54:56.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522198/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522198/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the oral contribution of the Minister for Immigration of 3 May 2016, Official Report, column 45WH, on asylum seeker dispersal policy, if she will publish the template letter she plans to send to leaders of local authorities on widening dispersal.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","38749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522199","Home Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Home Office and its accommodation providers encourage accommodated asylum seekers to inform us of any criminal or anti-social activity against them so that appropriate action can be taken to ensure their safety. Information concerning the reports of criminal offences is not recorded on centrally collated statistical databases and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost by examination of case records.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-15T11:03:25.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522199/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522199/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522199/answer/previousversion/2071","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of criminal offences against residents of properties used to house asylum seekers have been recorded in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","38729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522200","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>The provision of accommodation for asylum seekers is provided under the COMPASS contracts. It is the responsibility of all of the suppliers to ensure that all accommodation used meets the required contractual standard and complies with the Decent Homes Standards. The accommodation should be safe, habitable and fit for purpose. The COMPASS providers are required to inspect properties each month and UKVI's contract compliance teams reinforce this by visiting properties regularly.</p><p>The Home Office expects the highest standards and where a contractor is found to be falling short of these standards we work with them to ensure that issues are quickly addressed.</p><p>Earlier this year, we instructed our supplier (G4S) to repaint the doors of G4S and Jomast managed properties to ensure that no one colour is predominant. I have received confirmation from the Provider that this had been completed, UKVI staff have also confirmed that no one colour is predominant as they have visited properties as part of their inspection regime.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38728 ; 38900","2016-06-06T12:44:19.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522200/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522200/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Compass Contracts: Tees Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has made an assessment of the progress of the programme to re-paint the red doors of properties used to house asylum seekers on Teesside.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","38730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522201","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>There were 111 asylum applications from Yemeni nationals in 2015, and 15 in Quarter 1 (January to March) 2016.</p><p>There were 12 refusals of asylum or an alternative form of protection, at initial decision, to Yemeni nationals in Quarter 1 (January to March) 2016.</p><p>The Home Office publishes figures on asylum applications and initial decisions by nationality in the quarterly Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics, January to March 2016, is available from:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2016/asylum</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","38756","2016-06-06T16:17:03.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522201/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522201/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Asylum: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many claims for asylum from people from Yemen have been refused in 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522202","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>There were no escorted enforced returns to Yemen in 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T12:47:57.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522202/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522202/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Deportation: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which companies were contracted to facilitate enforced returns to Yemen for failed asylum seekers from that country in 2015.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522203","Home Office","false","2016-06-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave her on 14 April 2016, Question number 33999.</p><p>There were no enforced removals of nationals from Yemen in 2015 who had unsuccessfully claimed asylum.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-06T12:46:34.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522203/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522203/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Deportation: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on which dates in 2015 enforced removals of people from Yemen who had unsuccessfully claimed asylum took place.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","38743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522204","Home Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer given to Parliamentary Questions 38811 and 38825 by the hon. Member for Weston –Super-Mare (John Penrose), Parliamentary Secretary, Cabinet Office, on 8 June 2016.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-06-14T10:06:34.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522204/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522204/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Home Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from her Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material has been since 1 January 2016; and what she estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522205","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the Prime Minister's response of 25th May 2016 [37198]. This information is not collated centrally by the Department.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-06-09T12:02:05.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522205/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522205/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-26","Home Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 May 2016 to Question 37198, how many of the leaflets entitled Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK have been returned to her Department; and what the postage cost to the Government has been of such returns.","true","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","38774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522206","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-09","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the Prime Minister's response of 25th May 2016. This information is not collated centrally by the Department.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-06-09T12:34:28.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522206/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522206/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Department for International Development: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 25 May 2016 to Question 37198, how many of the leaflets entitled Why the Government believes that voting to remain in the European Union is the best decision for the UK have been returned to her Department; and what the postage cost to the Government has been of such returns.","true","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","38775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522207","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-09","<p>Copies of the Government's published documents on the Referendum are available in the Libraries of both Houses. It is not normal practice to publish letters to members of the public and stakeholders. Costs relating to the Referendum will be accounted for in the usual way in Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-06-09T12:35:03.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522207/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522207/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Department for International Development: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will place in the Library copies of all letters, leaflets and other material from her Department circulated to (a) stakeholders and (b) members of the public on the EU referendum; what the costs of the production and distribution of that material has been since 1 January 2016; and what she estimates the cost of any further production and distribution of such material will be between 6 May 2016 and 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","38822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522208","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-06","<p>It is in the interest of the UK taxpayer, as well as beneficiaries on the ground, ‎that the Department for International Development scrutinises the most cost-effective means of delivering aid, especially when responding to crises. In some cases technology can provide valuable advantages in terms of efficiency and cost effectiveness, as well as enabling the ability to respond rapidly to crises and assist those in the hardest to reach places.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has recently commissioned a review of the potential of a number of Frontier Technologies including Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) technology, which will help us identify potential applications as well as risks.</p><p> </p><p>There are a small number of examples of UAV technologies currently being trialled in DFID programmes. This includes a small-scale trial of UAV mapping to inform disaster preparedness, mitigation and response efforts in Nepal. There is also research being conducted in the natural and physical sciences arena, including on climate extremes which have an impact on vulnerable populations in developing countries.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","38661","2016-06-06T16:28:22.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522208/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522208/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Developing Countries: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the potential use and effectiveness of unmanned aerial vehicle technology in supporting the UK's international development agenda.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","38662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522209","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-06","<p>It is in the interest of the UK taxpayer, as well as beneficiaries on the ground, ‎that the Department for International Development scrutinises the most cost-effective means of delivering aid, especially when responding to crises. In some cases technology can provide valuable advantages in terms of efficiency and cost effectiveness, as well as enabling the ability to respond rapidly to crises and assist those in the hardest to reach places.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has recently commissioned a review of the potential of a number of Frontier Technologies including Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) technology, which will help us identify potential applications as well as risks.</p><p> </p><p>There are a small number of examples of UAV technologies currently being trialled in DFID programmes. This includes a small-scale trial of UAV mapping to inform disaster preparedness, mitigation and response efforts in Nepal. There is also research being conducted in the natural and physical sciences arena, including on climate extremes which have an impact on vulnerable populations in developing countries.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","38662","2016-06-06T16:28:22.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522209/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522209/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Humanitarian Aid: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is carrying out trials to assess the suitability of unmanned aerial vehicle technology as part of the UK's humanitarian disaster response capability.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","38661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522210","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-06","<p>The World Humanitarian Summit made real gains for gender equality in humanitarian responses. This was a priority of the UK at the Summit and our call to put gender equality at the heart of 21st century humanitarian action was loudly echoed by many. There was strong agreement on the need to go beyond protection and make sure girls and women have a voice, choice, and control, even when crises hit. New Member States joined the Call to Action on Gender-Based Violence in Emergencies (launched by UK in 2013) and commitments were made to ensure the right to sexual and reproductive health care is fulfilled for all women and adolescent girls in crisis settings.</p><p> </p><p>My colleague, the Secretary of State for International Development, has already given her impressions of the Summit in a Written Ministerial Statement to the House.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-06T16:21:53.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522210/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522210/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Developing Countries: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the outcomes of the World Humanitarian Summit on gender equality; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","38681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522211","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-09","<p>As set out in our UK Strategy to end violence against women and girls: 2016 to 2020 we are pursuing an ambitious programme of work at the international level. Scaling up efforts to eliminate VAWG requires global action and leadership. DFID is continuing to demonstrate leadership internationally, for example, at the World Humanitarian Summit the UK announced an expansion of the VAWG programme in Syria with UNFPA. DFID will continue to support VAWG interventions at country and central level where it is appropriate and where there is a comparative advantage for DFID to do so .</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-06-09T14:40:38.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522211/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522211/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department plans to increase the number of interventions to tackle violence against women and girls through programmes funded by her Department at (a) donor and (b) country level.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","38676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522212","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-09","<p>As part of the recent ICAI report on DFID’S efforts to eliminate violence against women and girls (VAWG), and building on a DFID mapping exercise from 2014, ICAI identified 127 VAWG programmes – up from 64 in 2012. The value of these programmes came to £184 million in 2015. The value for money question is specifically addressed in our pioneering violence against women and girls research and innovation programme called ‘What Works to Prevent Violence’, and we will be incorporating findings into programme development as they emerge.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-06-09T14:39:44.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522212/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522212/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-05-26","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made an assessment of (a) the adequacy of its expenditure on and (b) the value for money of its work on violence against women and girls.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","38656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522213","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-10","<p>There have been one hundred and fifty eight judgments made in England against County Court respondents with the word Tivium in their name. Forty three of those had judgements issued and entered at the County Court Money Claims Centre in the North West. There were no judgments recorded as being issued and entered in courts in Lancashire. A judgment is not necessarily made near to the claimant’s residential address. Data on how many judgements have been satisfied is not held.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-06-10T09:45:45.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522213/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522213/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-26","Tivium: Judgements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) court judgments have been made against Tivium and (b) such judgments have been satisfied in (i) England, (ii) the North West and (iii) Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","38659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522214","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Ministry of Justice is currently undertaking a post-implementation review of the impact of the introduction of fees in the Employment Tribunals. The review will report in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-06-06T15:37:48.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522214/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522214/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-05-26","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the methodology used to calculate the employment tribunal fees increase in preventing a reduction in the number of cases coming to tribunal.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","38619"
