"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521097","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-02","<p>Analysis undertaken by the independent Migration Advisory Committee in 2012 shows that higher levels of net migration will, all else equal, increase the growth rate of the potential labour supply and therefore the rate of growth of overall GDP.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-02T12:54:33.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521097/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521097/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Immigration: Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of economic growth generated as a direct result of immigration in the last five years; and what estimate he has made of the effect of immigration on the rate of economic growth in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","38166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521098","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) location decisions were based on a number of key principles to enable it to deliver more for less. These plans will generate estate savings of up to £100 million a year by 2025 across HMRC’s entire estate. It will do this at a lower cost to the taxpayer by using the best of modern technology and basing its staff in modern and more cost-effective buildings.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-02T16:22:32.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521098/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521098/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Revenue and Customs: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average cost of floor space (a) will be at the planned HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) office in Leeds and (b) is at the HMRC offices in Bradford.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","38167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521099","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>Lord Adonis was appointed to chair the shadow National Infrastructure Commission on an interim basis. The government is bringing forward legislation to create the NIC as an independent body, and will hold an open competition to appoint a permanent Chair, in line with the Code of Practice of the Commissioner for Public Appointments.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-06-06T14:39:10.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521099/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521099/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","National Infrastructure Commission: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the process is for the appointment of a new chair for the National Infrastructure Commission.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","38152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521100","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-06","<p>Her Majesty’s Government plan to lay the Investment Allowance and Cluster Area Allowance (Investment Expenditure) Regulations 2016 before Parliament after Parliament’s summer recess. This Statutory Instrument will bring certain leasing expenditure into the scope of the Investment Allowance and the Cluster Area Allowance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","38238","2016-06-06T14:28:09.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521100/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521100/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Investment Allowance and Cluster Area Allowance (Investment Expenditure) Regulations 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals bringing leasing expenditure into the scope of the investment allowance and cluster area allowance.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","38364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521101","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-01","<p>The government is committed to increasing competition in banking to improve outcomes for consumers. That is why we set up the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) as a single, stronger competition regulator, to promote competition and ensure markets work well for consumers, businesses and the wider economy.</p><p> </p><p>We support the CMA’s ambition to increase competition through its retail banking market investigation, including helping overdraft users understand the fees associated with overdrafts and mitigating the adverse effects of unarranged overdraft fees.</p><p> </p><p>The CMA’s investigation is ongoing and it is currently consulting on the provisional decision on remedies. The government welcomes the CMA’s work as a crucial step towards the goal of a highly competitive banking system, and stands ready to take action as necessary once the CMA publishes its final report in the summer.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-01T13:54:14.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521101/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521101/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Bank Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on competition between banks of the adoption of the recent recommendations of the Competition and Markets Authority on the capping of unarranged overdraft fees.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521102","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>We will consult on the appropriate compliance arrangements for the levy and will plan resource allocation in due course.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-26T15:49:01.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521102/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521102/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how he plans to fund the cost of implementation of the soft drinks industry levy in its first year.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","38342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521103","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-02","<p>The British people are asking for the facts before they decide whether to vote Remain or Leave in the EU referendum. Analysis published by HM Treasury shows the impact that a vote to leave the EU would</p><p>have on UK output and house prices. In the ‘shock scenario’, after two years, house prices would be 10% lower compared with a vote to remain in the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury is appropriately resourced to support the Government’s priorities in Europe. However, it is not practical to identify full-time equivalent staff numbers.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-06-02T10:05:31.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521103/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521103/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many officials of his Department were involved in the research, writing and production of his Department's recent analysis of the effect of Britain leaving the EU on the value of homes in the UK; and if he will estimate the cost to the public purse of the research and production of that analysis.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521104","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-27","<p>The new Lifetime ISA is an additional flexible savings product which will complement pensions to give savers greater freedom and choice to save for the long-term in a way that works for them.</p><p> </p><p>With automatic enrolment set to help nine million with their pension, the Government remains committed to supporting people who save in different ways.</p><p> </p><p>The Lifetime ISA supports the Government’s ambition to encourage a regular savings habit amongst young people and to create a culture of long-term saving.</p><p> </p><p>The Lifetime ISA is a voluntary product. For further information on the costing of this policy, please see page 9 of the Budget 2015 Policy Costings document: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-27T13:29:25.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521104/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521104/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Individual Savings Accounts: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 24 May 2016 to Question 37150, what assessment he has made of the effect of new lifetime ISA on changes in the levels of pension savings amongst young people.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","38340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521105","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>Health experts have identified sugar sweetened soft drinks as a major source of sugar in children’s and teenagers’ diet, and a cause of childhood obesity. The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) recommends that sugar only forms 5% of daily calories; however, for children, it is currently around 15%.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent published National Diet and Nutrition Survey (NDNS) reports that sugar sweetened soft drinks are the a major contributor to daily sugar intake for children, accounting for about 30% of the daily sugar intake alone.</p><p> </p><p>The soft drinks industry levy will encourage producers to reformulate soft drinks so that they contain less sugar.</p><p> </p><p>Industry data was used for the policy costing of the soft drinks industry levy announced at Budget 2016. Details are available at page 12 in the Budget 2016 policy costings document available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-26T15:55:55.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521105/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521105/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what data or research by industry analysts were used to inform the decision to introduce a soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","38335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521106","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-01","<p>The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments and their impact on the UK, including the debt operations of major countries, as part of the normal process of policy development.</p><p> </p><p>As one of the most open trading economies in the world with a large financial sector, we have to recognise that the UK is not immune to the external events in the world economy. This is precisely why the UK has been working through its long-term economic plan. Since 2010 the plan has been focussed on reducing the deficit and ensuring sound public finances, while delivering the supply side reforms necessary to improve long-term productivity growth. That has allowed an active monetary policy to support the economy while ensuring the fiscal position is sustainable in the long term.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-01T13:55:55.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521106/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521106/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-24","Debts: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on the economy of the UK of the recent dumping of US debt by China, Russia and Brazil.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521107","Church Commissioners","false","2016-05-26","<p>Churches across England have responded to the Archbishop of Canterbury’s call to support credit unions and other forms of responsible credit and savings. At least 31 out of 40 dioceses have been actively involved in supporting over 50 credit unions in various ways, such as:</p><ul><li>promoting the local credit union in their congregation and wider community</li><li>recruiting credit union volunteers</li><li>hosting training sessions</li><li>opening church premises as credit union access points</li><li>encouraging payroll savings schemes among local employers</li><li>helping to set up school savings clubs</li></ul><p> </p><p>Through the Church Credit Champions Network, one of the core initiatives of the Archbishop’s Task Group on Responsible Credit and Savings, the pilot scheme has engaged over 350 churches in London and Liverpool alone and trained more than 260 Credit Champions to date. Other creative diocesan responses include the Murston Community Bank in Canterbury diocese, Lichfield’s Funeral Project, Southwell &amp; Nottingham’s 100x100 scheme are all designed to raise local awareness of credit unions.</p><p> </p><p>The other core initiative, the LifeSavers programme, is working with eight credit unions across the country to set up savings clubs in primary schools, alongside an integrated programme of financial education. Following a successful pilot, the programme is being rolled out to 120 church and non-church primary schools over the next three academic years with financial support from Virgin Money. Additional funding from Government will help extend the coverage to many more primary schools through a dedicated LifeSavers website.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-05-26T15:51:08.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521107/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521107/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-05-24","Churches: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, how many credit unions have approached churches or church organisations as a result of the Archbishop of Canterbury's #TOYOURCREDIT initiative.","false","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","38145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521108","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-01","<p>The Government has no plans to put in place reforms in this situation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-01T15:30:18.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521108/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521108/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his plans are for the reform of leaseholds related to properties with two households in one building where the freehold is held by one owner; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","38168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521109","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-26","<p>As is the case with the existing Right to Buy, the voluntary agreement with housing associations and the National Housing Federation to extend Right to Buy discounts to housing association tenants will not apply to those people who already own a share in their home.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-26T13:36:24.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521109/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521109/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will extend the Right to Buy discount to housing association tenants who already own a share of their property.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","38170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521110","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-08","<p>The tables below are the average hourly rates for all employees (Senior Civil Service and below within my department for the following categories. However, I would note to the Hon. Member that such simple averages do not paint an accurate figure of our workforce and recruitment practices.</p><p><strong>2015</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Category</p></td><td><p>Average hourly rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>£18.39</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>£21.05</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Undeclared</p></td><td><p>£19.92</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>2016</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Category</p></td><td><p>Average hourly rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>£18.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>£20.83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Undeclared</p></td><td><p>£20.79</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The Civil Service is changing, and our recruitment seeks to reflect the make-up and composition of our nation as a whole. Historically, BME staff were under-represented: both in terms of previous recruitment patterns and the number and proportion in higher grades, both of these factors have contributed to the differences in average salaries.</p><p>We are making progress the proportion of BME staff in the Civil Service has risen from 9.2% in 2010 to 10.6% in 2015, but we recognise that there is still more to do.</p><p>In March, the Government published its 2016 Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service. It provides a progress update on initiatives to increase diversity in the Civil Service, including cross-Government talent programmes aimed at under-represented groups.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/talent-action-plan-2016-removing-the-barriers-to-success" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/talent-action-plan-2016-removing-the-barriers-to-success</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-08T15:40:47.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521110/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521110/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Department for Communities and Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the average hourly earnings were of his Department's (a) BME and (b) non-BME employees in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","38215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521111","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-02","<p>Details of Ministerial overseas travel, and senior officials' business expenses are published on a quarterly basis. The remaining information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-02T16:23:47.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521111/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521111/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Department for Communities and Local Government: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many visits (a) Ministers and (b) officials in his Department have made to Coventry in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","38323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521112","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-06","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework is clear that local planning authorities should set out the strategic priorities for the area in the Local Plan. This should include strategic policies to deliver the provision of infrastructure for energy. The Framework asks local planning authorities to identify opportunities where development can draw its energy supply from decentralised, renewable or low carbon energy supply systems and for co-locating potential heat customers and suppliers. The Framework is supported by planning guidance on renewable and low carbon energy, which sets out how decentralised energy opportunities can be identified. The National Planning Policy Framework and guidance can be found here - <a href="http://planningguidance.communities.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://planningguidance.communities.gov.uk/</a>.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-06T13:50:57.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521112/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521112/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Power Stations: Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department provides to local authorities on planning for the location of new decentralised power generation plants.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","38402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521113","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-02","<p>Since 2010 we have invested over £500 million to enable local authorities and the voluntary sector to support those vulnerable and at risk of homelessness.</p><p>One person without a home is one too many and we are committed to do all we can to prevent homelessness. We have protected the homelessness prevention funding local authorities receive, totalling £315 million by 2019-20. This builds on our Spending Review commitment to increase central government funding to £139 million over the next four years. We are working with homelessness organisations to consider all options, including legislation, to ensure those at risk of homelessness get earlier and more effective support.</p><p>We also announced in the Budget £100 million to deliver low cost ‘move on’ accommodation to enable people leaving hostels and refuges to make a sustainable recovery from a homelessness crisis, providing at least 2,000 places for vulnerable people to enable independent living.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-02T14:15:36.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521113/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521113/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department has spent on tackling homelessness in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","38328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521114","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-02","<p>The Secretary of State has written to all Local Enterprise Partnerships setting out the basis for which awards will be made in this round of Growth Deals. The letter sets out the criteria that will be used in assessment, which include demonstrating strong collaboration across the local area, strong governance, engagement with key government objectives, and delivery of existing Growth Deals. A copy of this letter will be placed in the Library of the House. The outcomes of this round of funding will be published on the Government’s website.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-06-02T14:55:12.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521114/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521114/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Local Growth Deals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Answer of 25 April 2016 to Question 34445, if he will publish on his Department's website the basis on which further Local Growth Fund awards will be made later in 2016; and what criteria his Department uses to assess competitively bids for that fund.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","38192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521115","Home Office","false","2016-06-21","<p>HM Government does not collect information on the funding of religious institutions in the UK. If such institutions, in England and Wales, are registered charities with the Charity Commission and have an annual income of over £25,000, their accounts are made publically available on the charity’s entry on the Public Register of Charities, which is accessible from www.charitycommission.gov.uk</p><p>In addition to the requirement to file accounts, the Charity Commission, as the charity regulator in England and Wales, can review and inspect the financial records of charities to ensure that their trustees comply with their duty to account. The Prime Minister last year commissioned a review into the funding of extremism in the UK. This will examine specifically the nature, scale and origin of Islamist extremist activity in the UK including any overseas sources.</p><p>In December last year, the Prime Minister commented on the conclusions of the Muslim Brotherhood Review that was commissioned to improve the Government’s understanding of the Group. The Government will keep under review the views that are promoted and activities that are undertaken by Muslim Brotherhood associates in the UK.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-06-21T09:31:17.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521115/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521115/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-24","Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential link between the foreign-funded Islamic cultural centres in the UK and the Muslim Brotherhood; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521116","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-02","<p>The Prime Minister has commissioned a review into the funding of extremism in the UK, including funding that comes from overseas.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-02T14:11:36.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521116/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521116/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on the foreign-funding of Islamic cultural centres in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521117","Home Office","false","2016-06-09","<p>HM Government does not collect information on the funding of religious institutions in the UK. If such institutions, in England and Wales, are registered charities with the Charity Commission and have an annual income of over £25,000, their accounts are made publically available on the charity’s entry on the Public Register of Charities, which is accessible from www.charitycommission.gov.uk</p><p>In addition to the requirement to file accounts, the Charity Commission, as the charity regulator in England and Wales, can review and inspect the financial records of charities to ensure that their trustees comply with their duty to account.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-06-09T17:11:25.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521117/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521117/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-05-24","Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish a list of all Islamic cultural centres in the UK primarily funded by foreign donations; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521118","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-02","<p>We are not aware of any Government financial support given to Qatar Charity in the last five years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-02T14:05:24.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521118/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521118/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-24","Qatar Charity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what (a) financial support and (b) other support the Government has given to Qatar Charity in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","38376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521119","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>Responsibility for safety at football grounds in Scotland is devolved so any discussions would be for the Scottish Government. I meet regularly with the Football Association, the Sports Grounds Safety Authority (who are responsible for safety at sports grounds in England and Wales) and others to discuss those safety issues for which I am responsible.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-06-06T12:55:19.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521119/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521119/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","Football: Hooliganism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will hold urgent discussions with the football authorities in England and Scotland on the implications of the events at Hampden Park, Glasgow at the Scottish Cup final in May 2016 for his Department's policies on preventing football hooliganism.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","38268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521120","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>The BBC receives over £3.7 billion of public money each year through the licence fee. As set out in the Government's White Paper, A BBC for the future: a Broadcaster of Distinction, the government encourages the BBC to do more to open up its archive and ensure that it can be used by the public and as wide a range of institutions and organisations as possible. ​How the BBC uses the public money it receives to achieve this is matter for the BBC.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T16:00:40.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521120/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521120/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","BBC: Archives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 73 of his Department's White Paper, A BBC for the future, published in May 2016, what steps he is taking to ensure that the BBC archive is made accessible to as wide a range of institutions and organisations as possible; and what funding his Department plans to provide to support that aim.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","38404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521121","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The independent television production sector in this country is a fantastic success story, generating around £3 billion in revenue each year. I have considered carefully Ofcom’s report on the television production sector and decided that the regulations continue to be effective and play a key role in supporting a diverse and vibrant production sector. We have therefore decided to make no change.</p>","Maldon","Mr John Whittingdale",,"2016-05-26T14:53:44.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521121/answer","Biography information for Mr John Whittingdale","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521121/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","Ofcom: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to make an announcement on Ofcom's review of the Terms of Trade.","false","Biography information for Jesse Norman","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","38331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521122","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-02","<p>As of 1 May 2016, over £476m of BDUK funding had been spent on Phase 1 of the superfast broadband programme. Funding is released on completion of project delivery milestones. The remainder of the funding will be spent by end 2017 which is the completion date for some of the Phase 1 projects.</p>","Maldon","Mr John Whittingdale",,"2016-06-02T14:53:05.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521122/answer","Biography information for Mr John Whittingdale","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521122/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","Broadband: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much of £530 million his Department allocated to Broadband Delivery UK remained unspent at the end of the Phase 1 broadband delivery period.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","38125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521123","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-15","$24052016|5|W|26052016|Greg Mulholland|Leeds North West|To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the average hourly earnings were of his Department's (a) BME and (b) non-BME employees in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016. 38216 A: The tables below are the average hourly rates for all employees (Senior Civil Service and below) within the Department of Culture, Media and Sport for the following categories. However, I would note to the Hon. Member that such simple averages do not paint an accurate figure of our workforce and recruitment practices.<p> </p><p>2015</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Category</p></td><td><p>Average hourly rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>£17.06</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>£21.63</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>£20.20</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>2016</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Category</p></td><td><p>Average hourly rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>£16.50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>£21.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>£20.39</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Civil Service is changing, and our recruitment seeks to reflect the make-up and composition of our nation as a whole. Historically, BME staff were under-represented: both in terms of previous recruitment patterns and the number and proportion in higher grades, both of these factors have contributed to the differences in average salaries.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally in DCMS a significant number of employees have not declared their ethnicity - less than 60% declared their ethnicity in 2015 and 2016 – which means that the data provided cannot be taken as a comparison of BME and non-BME wages across the Department. DCMS are actively encouraging employees to increase the declarations that will provide reliable data on protected characteristics. As a result between 31 March and 27 May 2016 the declarations have risen to almost 70%. There is also a clear decline in the pay gap between BME and non-BME employees over the two months that the declarations have increased.</p><p> </p><p>The differential at Senior Civil Service (SCS) grades is a result of a low number of declared BME employees at this level.</p><p> </p><p>We are making progress the proportion of BME staff in the Civil Service has risen from 9.2% in 2010 to 10.6% in 2015, but we recognise that there is still more to do.</p><p>In March, the Government published its 2016 Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service. It provides a progress update on initiatives to increase diversity in the Civil Service, including cross-Government talent programmes aimed at under-represented groups.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/talent-action-plan-2016-removing-the-barriers-to-success" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/talent-action-plan-2016-removing-the-barriers-to-success</a></p><p> </p><p>31 March 2015 Data</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>2015</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grade</p></td><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>Unknown</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SCS</p></td><td><p>34.42</p></td><td><p>35.68</p></td><td><p>40.51</p></td><td><p>35.26</p></td><td><p>37.24</p></td><td><p>41.17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A(U)</p></td><td><p>32.62</p></td><td><p>28.54</p></td><td><p>29.49</p></td><td><p>28.37</p></td><td><p>29.89</p></td><td><p>29.61</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A</p></td><td><p>24.52</p></td><td><p>24.42</p></td><td><p>24.96</p></td><td><p>24.17</p></td><td><p>24.26</p></td><td><p>24.56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>B</p></td><td><p>17.07</p></td><td><p>17.06</p></td><td><p>16.61</p></td><td><p>17.09</p></td><td><p>16.74</p></td><td><p>16.10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>C</p></td><td><p>12.48</p></td><td><p>12.31</p></td><td><p>12.22</p></td><td><p>11.73</p></td><td><p>12.22</p></td><td><p>12.12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>D</p></td><td><p>9.92</p></td><td><p>10.50</p></td><td><p>9.94</p></td><td><p>9.93</p></td><td><p>9.68</p></td><td><p>10.03</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes on the data</p><p> </p><p>The data is sourced from the Staff in Post payroll reports for 31 March 2015 and 31 March 2016. ‘Employees’ include all employees paid through the organisation’s payroll, including any employees on maternity, paternity or shared parental leave, those on paid sick leave and employees on paid special leave. This excludes employees not paid through the payroll including agency and interim staff, those on unpaid leave or career breaks, Fee Paid staff, Non-Executive Board Members, political appointments where earnings are not determined by DCMS such as Ministers and Special Advisors.</p><p> </p><p>‘Unknown’ includes individuals who have either elected to prefer not to declare their ethnicity or those who have not recorded a response against this protected characteristic. The average hourly earnings include basic salary and allowances.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-15T12:35:01.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521123/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521123/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the average hourly earnings were of his Department's (a) BME and (b) non-BME employees in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","38216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521124","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-02","<p>The Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) produces guidance for organisations on their obligations under the Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA). This guidance is used by the Information Commissioner’s staff when assessing concerns and complaints from the public under S42 of the DPA.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, staff receive formal training to ensure that consistent outcomes are achieved in decision making.</p>","Maldon","Mr John Whittingdale",,"2016-06-02T14:54:54.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521124/answer","Biography information for Mr John Whittingdale","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521124/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","Information Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what mechanisms the Information Commissioner's Office has in place to ensure decisions of staff of that Office are compliant with Section 42 of the Data Protection Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","38213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521125","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-27","To date, Fastershire have spent almost £17m of the £18.2m BDUK funding allocation. The project is on track to complete by December 2016.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-27T09:26:54.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521125/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521125/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-24","Broadband: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much of the funding allocated by Broadband Delivery UK to Fastershire remained unspent at the end of the Phase 1 broadband delivery period.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","38162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521126","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-06","<p>None. The deployment of the police is a Home Office responsibility.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-06T15:35:59.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521126/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521126/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Security: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many security and military personnel and police have been deployed from other EU member states to respond to emergencies and other security threats in the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","38154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521127","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-26T16:19:15.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521127/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521127/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Ministry of Defence: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average hourly earnings were of his Department's (a) BME and (b) non-BME employees in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","38217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521128","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>The Ministry of Defence has seen published reports in relation to this incident, which is one of a number of such attacks against medical facilities in opposition-held eastern Aleppo since 22 April. We condemn any intentional targeting of medical facilities and, while we are not able to comment on the detail of this particular incident, we consider it likely that most of these attacks have been carried out by the Regime or its backers.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:52:38.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521128/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521128/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information he holds on the airstrike that hit a Médecins Sans Frontières Hospital in Aleppo on 28 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","38177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521129","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>There has been no credible evidence or report of civilian casualties as a result of UK airstrikes in Syria since the UK military campaign started.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-05-31T14:54:15.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521129/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521129/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civilian deaths have been recorded from UK airstrikes in Syria since the UK military campaign started.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","38178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521130","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>The Royal Navy conducts routine deployments in the Atlantic region. However, for reasons of safeguarding national security, we do not discuss the detail of such operations, as this would or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p><p>The Royal Navy also maintains a permanent presence in the South Atlantic in the form of the Falkland Islands Patrol Vessel, HMS CLYDE, supported by a Royal Fleet Auxiliary ship. The Royal Navy's Ice Patrol Ship, HMS PROTECTOR, also operates in the South Atlantic region for periods of the year.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:52:14.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521130/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521130/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Warships: South Atlantic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects to deploy a Type 23 Frigate or Type 45 Destroyer as part of the South Atlantic Patrol Tasking.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","38134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521131","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Statement I made on 24 May 2016 (Official Report, column 401).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-31T14:51:04.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521131/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521131/answer","20160524_UQ_on_Yemen_Cluster_Munitions[2].docx","20160524_UQ_on_Yemen_Cluster_Munitions[2].docx","Hansard extract on Yemen: Cluster Munitions","Hansard extract on Yemen: Cluster Munitions","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521131/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effect of the use of UK-supplied BL-755 cluster munitions by the Saudi Arabian-led coalition on the civilian population in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","38314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521132","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>Full details of trained and untrained strengths of the UK Armed Forces are included in the UK Armed Forces Monthly Service Personnel Statistics, which can be found at the following address:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-monthly-service-personnel-statistics-2016</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-05-31T14:54:42.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521132/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521132/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the strength of full-time members of the (a) army, (b) Royal Navy and (c) Royal Air Force was on 1 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","38262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521133","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-02","<p>Members of the Armed Forces routinely deploy overseas on operational duties or to conduct other Defence activities. The scope, scale and timeframes of some of these deployments mean that it is not always possible to provide comprehensive lists.</p><p>The answer to part (i) is provided in the attached map and is accurate as at 6 May 2016. We are, however, unable to break this down by Service.</p><p>The answer to part (ii) will take longer to assemble. I will write to the hon. Member in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-02T14:53:32.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521133/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521133/answer","Annex A to PQ38263-MOD Deployments Map.png","Annex A to PQ38263-MOD Deployments Map.png","Map to support PQ38263 - Armed Forces deployments","Map to support PQ38263 - Armed Forces deployments","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521133/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the (a) army, (b) Royal Navy and (c) Royal Air Force were deployed to which countries on (i) 1 May 2016 and (ii) during 2015.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","38263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521134","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-06","<p>My hon. Friend the Minister of State for the Armed Forces visited 38 Brigade on 26 May 2015. No other Defence Ministers visited military establishments in Northern Ireland during 2015.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-06-06T15:08:06.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521134/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521134/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Military Bases: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions Ministers of his Department visited military establishments in Northern Ireland during 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","38266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521135","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-02","<p>Since the withdrawal of the Nimrod MR2 in March 2010, we have drawn on other military assets, including Type 23 Frigates, submarines and Merlin Anti-Submarine Warfare helicopters and, where appropriate and possible, assistance from allies. We will continue the present practice of issuing requests to allies to provide Maritime Patrol Aircraft when there is an operational need to do so.</p><p>Our allies are well aware of the value of such reciprocal support and there are also many instances of the UK providing support to others. Examples include Quick Reaction Alert aircraft for Baltic Air Policing and the integration of HMS KENT into a French carrier group deployment to the Gulf last year</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","38261","2016-06-02T11:17:15.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521135/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521135/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of UK allies providing maritime patrol aircraft for use in the UK in advance of the delivery of new P8 aircraft.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","38258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521136","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>The Ministry of Defence Police (MDP) provides services by arrangement to the United States Visiting Forces. The US Authorities are responsible for bearing the cost of the services of the MDP deployed on operational duty at RAF bases in the UK that are made available to the United States Visiting Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:53:13.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521136/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521136/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, who pays for the services of the Ministry of Defence Police when they work on US bases in the UK.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","38278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521137","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>All Ministry of Defence (MOD) Police Officers deployed on operational duty at RAF bases in the UK that are made available to the United States Visiting Forces are directly accountable to, and under the direction and control of the Chief Constable MOD Police.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:53:46.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521137/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521137/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, to whom Ministry of Defence Police working on US bases in the UK are directly accountable.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","38279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521138","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Statement made by my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State (Michael Fallon) on 8 January 2015.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:44:57.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521138/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521138/answer","Hansard_Extract_8_January_2015.[1].docx","Hansard_Extract_8_January_2015.[1].docx","Hansard extract on Infrastructure Review","Hansard extract on Infrastructure Review","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521138/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","RAF Croughton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the proposed redevelopment of USAF Croughton by the US has been confirmed to him.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","38280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521139","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-01","<p>The Intelligence and Security Committee does not comment on the details of its work programme. Where appropriate it publishes information on visits it has undertaken in its Annual Reports.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","38415","2016-06-01T14:02:43.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521139/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521139/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-24","Intelligence and Security Committee: RAF Menwith Hill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when any member of the Intelligence and Security Committee last visited NSA/NRO Menwith Hill in their capacity as a member of that committee.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","38281"
